{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527696"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:32:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:32:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14217"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14217"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.84,0.04,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14217"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41050"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"2909"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of decreased urine output and lower abdominal discomfort. He has a medical history of hypertension and a 40 pack-year smoking history. His regular medications include amlodipine and aspirin. He reports intermittent painless haematuria over the past three months but has not sought medical attention for this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.5\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended and tender in the suprapubic region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 450 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum urea: 25 mmol/L (3.0-8.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 5.6 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 98 g/L (130-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltrasound of the kidneys and bladder shows bilateral hydronephrosis and hydroureters. The bladder appears to have an irregular wall thickening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s renal impairment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benign prostatic hyperplasia","Bladder cancer","Renal calculi","Retroperitoneal fibrosis","Medication-related nephrotoxicity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of acute kidney injury (AKI) and findings suggestive of post-renal obstruction. The most likely cause of his renal impairment is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebladder cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. Several factors support this diagnosis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. History of painless haematuria: This is a classic symptom of bladder cancer, especially in older adults with a smoking history. \u003Cbr /\u003E2. Bilateral hydronephrosis and hydroureters on ultrasound: This indicates obstruction at or below the level of the bladder. \u003Cbr /\u003E3. Irregular bladder wall thickening on ultrasound. \u003Cbr /\u003E4. Risk factors: The patient is a 68-year-old man with a significant smoking history, both of which are risk factors for bladder cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH)\u003C/strong\u003E can cause lower urinary tract symptoms and, in severe cases, post-renal AKI. However, BPH typically causes gradual onset of symptoms and is less likely to cause painless haematuria or irregular bladder wall thickening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal calculi\u003C/strong\u003E can cause obstruction and AKI, but they typically cause severe, colicky pain and are unlikely to cause bilateral obstruction simultaneously. The ultrasound findings are more consistent with a bladder-level obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause bilateral ureteral obstruction, but it is a rare condition and typically presents with back or flank pain. The bladder wall thickening seen on ultrasound is not typical of retroperitoneal fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedication-related nephrotoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is always a consideration in AKI, but the patient\u0027s medication list does not include common nephrotoxic drugs. Moreover, the ultrasound findings of obstruction and bladder wall thickening are not explained by medication-induced kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe next steps in management would include urgent urinary catheterisation to relieve the obstruction, followed by further imaging (such as CT urogram) to confirm the diagnosis and stage the suspected bladder cancer. Urology consultation would be required for definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder cancer is a cause of post-renal acute kidney injury in elderly patients."],"references":["Goyal A, Daneshpajouhnejad P, Hashmi MF, Bashir K. Acute kidney injury (acute renal failure). In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441896/","Bengtsen M B, Farkas D K, Borre M, S\u00c3\u00b8rensen H T, N\u00c3\u00b8rgaard M. Acute urinary retention and risk of cancer: population based Danish cohort study BMJ 2021;375:n2305. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/375/bmj.n2305"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41050"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14217"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41050"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T12:12:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T12:12:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6903"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55510"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api